You’re already thinking along the right invariant: local specialization + global exchange. When systems like that stabilize, a recurring geometry shows up—a hub-and-spoke network with cross-links, sometimes called a scale-free / small-world network. It’s the structure seen in cities (downtown + neighborhoods), research fields (journals + labs), package ecosystems (registries + libraries), and neural networks (dense hubs + sparse long-range links).

Below is a Pantheon-compatible, reversible implementation sketch you could drop into the repo.

⸻

Pantheon Knowledge Market Geometry (v0.1)

1) Network Shape

                 Grand Bazaar (Discovery Hub)
                     /   |   |   |   \
                    /    |   |   |    \
        Pattern Market  Code Market  Proof Market
             |              |            |
        (local hubs)   (local hubs)  (local hubs)
             |              |            |
           Campfires → Artifact Forge → Local Listings

Principle:
	•	Many small markets (specialized hubs).
	•	One Grand Bazaar (index + discovery).
	•	Cross-links between artifacts across markets.

This yields:
	•	fast discovery
	•	modular growth
	•	resilience if one node fails

⸻

2) Artifact Card as the Atomic Unit

Every tradable object is an Artifact Card.

Example (artifact.yaml):

artifact_id: pantheon.translation_engine.v0.1
name: Invariant Translation Engine
author: Thanatos Prime
market: translation
status: prototype

inputs:
  - text
  - json
  - yaml

outputs:
  - python
  - mermaid_graph
  - structured_prose

invariants_preserved:
  - entity_relations
  - constraints
  - intent

dependencies:
  - thought_object.schema.json

signals:
  reuse_count: 0
  adaptations: 0
  cross_market_links: []

reversibility:
  source_trace: true

This format keeps artifacts:
	•	machine readable
	•	composable
	•	traceable
	•	reversible

⸻

3) Grand Bazaar Index

The Grand Bazaar is just an index of artifact cards.

Example:

bazaar_index:
  markets:
    - pattern
    - code
    - translation
    - workflow
    - proof
    - interface

  artifacts:
    - pantheon.translation_engine.v0.1
    - pantheon.thought_object.schema

Its job is discovery, not governance.

⸻

4) Local Market Structure

Each market is simply a directory:

pantheon_marketplace/
  markets/
    pattern/
    code/
    translation/
    workflow/
    proof/
    interface/

Each market contains artifact cards and optional implementations.

Example:

markets/
  translation/
    translation_engine/
      artifact.yaml
      README.md
      prototype.py


⸻

5) Cross-Market Linking

Artifacts can reference other artifacts.

Example:

dependencies:
  - pantheon.translation_engine.v0.1
  - pantheon.pattern_prime.schema

This naturally creates a knowledge graph.

The Spider daemon could later visualize this graph.

